Central configuration for qubes-salt-config.

Qubes dom0 does not reliably load custom Salt *pillar* (a plain top.sls in a
pillar_root does not register with Qubes' topd/_tops mechanism and can even
break pillar loading entirely). So — like qusal — this project does NOT use
pillar. All user configuration lives here and is imported by states:

    {% from 'config.jinja' import cfg with context %}
    {{ cfg.qvm.debian.version }}
    {{ cfg.mirror.enabled }}

Edit the values below to customise your environment. This file is deployed to
/srv/salt/slchris/config.jinja and read directly (no pillar, no top.sls).

NOTE: no "#" comments are allowed INSIDE the {% set %} block below — Jinja has
no line comments inside expressions and dies with "unexpected char '#'".
Document keys here instead.

tailscale — remote access over a Tailscale mesh whose control plane is a
SELF-HOSTED Headscale (not Tailscale SaaS). One dedicated sys-tailscale
ProxyVM acts as the tailnet gateway: sys-net -> sys-firewall -> sys-tailscale
-> AppVMs. See mgmt/tailscale/README.md. Deploy requires rerunning
scripts/setup.sh. Keys:
  template        tailscaled is installed IN this template
  netvm           upstream NetVM for the gateway
  login_server    public HTTPS URL of your Headscale; the client only needs
                  --login-server, everything else is identical to SaaS
  auth_key        pre-auth key from `headscale preauthkeys create --user <id>
                  --reusable --expiration 720h`. Prefer NOT committing a real
                  key: leave "" and paste it once via the qube (see README
                  "Joining"), or fill it for full automation.
  accept_dns      use MagicDNS (100.100.100.100)
  hostname        tailnet node name; "" => qube name
  advertise_exit_node  let remote tailnet devices route all traffic out here
  advertise_routes     expose these CIDRs to the tailnet (must be approved on
                       the Headscale side: headscale nodes approve-routes),
                       e.g. ["10.137.0.0/16"]
                       CURRENT VALUE ["10.31.0.0/24"] is the whole internal LAN,
                       and that is a deliberate, informed choice — not a default
                       nobody looked at. It is what removes the need for a
                       separately-configured VPN: any device already on the
                       tailnet reaches the internal network directly.
                       What it GRANTS, stated plainly so narrowing it later is a
                       decision rather than a rediscovery: every tailnet device
                       can reach EVERY host on 10.31.0.0/24, including the PVE
                       management interfaces (10.31.0.200-205:8006), the ingress
                       (10.31.0.253) and the artifact store (10.31.0.2) which
                       serves the agent .deb over unauthenticated plain HTTP.
                       A tailnet node is therefore as trusted as a machine
                       plugged into the LAN. To narrow: replace with the
                       individual /32s actually needed (e.g. ["10.31.0.253/32",
                       "10.31.0.252/32"]) and re-run
                       `headscale nodes approve-routes` — the old broad route
                       stays approved on the Headscale side until you do.
  accept_routes   accept routes/exit-nodes advertised by other tailnet nodes
  forward_downstream_dns  DNS set inside sys-tailscale does NOT propagate to
                  AppVMs using it as NetVM; when True, downstream :53 is
                  DNAT'd to the tailnet resolver so they resolve MagicDNS
  ssh             "sshd" = plain key-only sshd in the gateway, reach it at its
                  100.x address (robust default with Headscale today);
                  "tailscale" = Tailscale SSH (verify your Headscale supports
                  it first); "none" = no SSH from the gateway
  authorized_keys [] => inherit cfg.remote_debug.authorized_keys

remote_debug.lan_subnet — which client subnets may reach the forwarded SSH
port on sys-net. Accepts a single CIDR string OR a list of them; one DNAT rule
is emitted per entry. Use a list when this machine moves between networks
(e.g. a wired LAN and a phone hotspot): a value that does not match the network
you are actually on means the DNAT never fires and you lose remote access, and
because scripts/setup.sh replaces /srv/salt/slchris wholesale, a deploy will
overwrite whatever was hand-edited on dom0. Keep every subnet you use here.

remotevm.targets / remotevm.services — these two lists ARE the local qrexec
policy. mgmt.remotevm.policy renders one rule per (service x target x source)
and nothing else; leaving either list empty renders a policy file with no rules
at all, and every cross-machine call then fails with "Request refused". That is
the state this file shipped in, and it is why qrexec admin calls from the relay
were refused: a configuration gap, not a missing feature.
  targets   one entry per RemoteVM. local_name is the qube name dom0 knows;
            remote_name is that qube's own name on the remote host (they may
            differ, QubesDB /remote/<local_name> holds the mapping); host is the
            SSH destination the relay uses to reach the remote host.
            dom0 has NO way to discover a qube the console provisioned — the
            console writes terraform, not qvm-prefs — so anything not listed
            here is simply unreachable from this machine no matter how healthy
            it is on the PVE side. Keep it in step with the console's fleet.
            host is consumed ONLY by mgmt.remotevm.relay (the SSHProxy
            transport), which writes it into the relay's ~/.ssh/config. The
            gRPC transport (mgmt.remotevm.grpc-relay) ignores it and dials
            remotevm.grpc.remote_endpoint instead. Fill host from the address
            terraform reports before applying the SSHProxy relay state; an
            empty host renders "HostName " and every ssh attempt fails.
  services  the allow-list of qrexec services the local side may invoke on a
            RemoteVM. Each entry punches a cross-machine hole, so list only
            services that are actually IMPLEMENTED on the remote. Today that is
            exactly one: qubesair.Ping (remote/qubes-rpc/qubesair.Ping in the
            qubes-air repo), the reachability probe the console's
            QubeService.CheckReachable calls.
            action MUST be "allow" for qubesair.Ping, not the "ask" default:
            CheckReachable runs unattended behind an HTTP request, so an "ask"
            rule would pop a dom0 prompt nobody is there to answer and the probe
            would time out and report a healthy qube as unreachable.
            Do NOT add qubesair.Status. It was in the agent's allowlist before
            anything implemented it, so every agent logged a "service allowed
            but missing" warning on every start; it was removed deliberately.
            Add it back here in the same change that ships an actual
            /etc/qubes-rpc/qubesair.Status.

remotevm.allowed_sources — which LOCAL qubes may make those calls. "@anyvm"
combined with an "allow" action means any qube on this machine, including a
disposable that just opened an attachment, can reach the remote fleet, and it
also makes the trailing "deny @anyvm" rule that policy.sls emits unreachable.
Scoped to the console qube, which is the only thing that needs it.

qubesair — the Qubes Air console: a DEDICATED template plus an AppVM built from
it. Deliberately NOT mgmt-jump. mgmt-jump accepts inbound SSH (see
remote_debug), and a qube anyone on the LAN can knock on must not also hold the
PVE API credentials, the agent CA private key, and the terraform state that
together can rebuild the whole remote fleet.
  enabled       master switch; the qubesair states no-op when False, so the rest
                of this block can be filled in and reviewed before deploying.
  template_source  the salt directory to clone the template FROM (not the
                template name — utils/macros/clone-template.sls resolves it via
                <dir>/template.jinja). debian-minimal resolves to
                debian-13-minimal, the only base present on this machine.
  template      name of the cloned template. Keep the tpl- prefix: that is what
                clone_template() produces, and a mismatch means the create state
                silently builds an AppVM on the wrong template.
  qube          the console AppVM. Must differ from `template` — Qubes qube
                names are a single global namespace, so reusing the name makes
                qvm-create fail.
  netvm         sys-tailscale, so the console sits behind the tailnet gateway
                and an operator on the tailnet is one hop away. sys-tailscale's
                own upstream is sys-firewall, so LAN reachability to PVE is
                unchanged. NOTE the ordering dependency this creates: deploy
                mgmt.tailscale BEFORE the qubesair states, or qvm-prefs netvm
                fails on a qube that does not exist. Set to "sys-firewall" if
                you are deploying the console without the tailnet.
  dns           10.31.0.252, the internal resolver. This is NOT cosmetic: Qubes'
                default forwarders (10.139.1.1/2) do not resolve
                pve.infra.plz.ac, and the obvious workaround — pointing
                pve_endpoint at 10.31.0.253 directly — throws away hostname
                validation of a perfectly good Let's Encrypt certificate on the
                one connection that carries the PVE API token. Fixing DNS keeps
                the name, and therefore keeps the certificate meaningful.
  memory/maxmem/vcpus  sizing. terraform is the memory consumer here, not the
                console; a plan over a few dozen qubes plus the bpg/proxmox
                provider wants noticeably more than the 400MB the other AppVMs
                in this file use.
  private_size  the AppVM private volume. The default 2G does not comfortably
                hold the terraform provider cache (~200MB), the .terraform
                directory, the SQLite database and the agent identity documents
                at once, and terraform's failure mode when it runs out of space
                mid-apply is a half-applied state file.
  listen        host:port the console binds. Loopback by default: the console
                has NO TLS and its API token is the only thing in front of it,
                so binding 0.0.0.0 publishes an unencrypted control plane for
                the entire fleet to the LAN. Reach it over SSH port-forward.
  data_dir      persistent root for everything the console writes. An AppVM's
                root volume is RESET on every reboot — only /rw and /home
                survive — so the database, keys and terraform state must live
                under /rw or they are silently recreated empty after a restart.
                Files that must appear elsewhere in the filesystem (unit files,
                /etc/qubes-rpc services) are bind-mounted from here via
                bind-dirs, the same pattern mgmt.tailscale.configure uses.
  database_dsn  SQLite path. Env: QUBES_AIR_DATABASE_DSN.
  orchestrator_enabled  False makes the console a mock: start/stop flip the
                database row and never invoke terraform. True is what actually
                provisions, and it makes terraform_dir mandatory (the console
                refuses to start otherwise).
  terraform_dir the terraform root the console shells out in. Env:
                QUBES_AIR_TERRAFORM_DIR.
  terraform_var_file  the OPERATOR-owned base var-file: endpoint, node, zone
                toggles. It must NOT define remote_qubes.
  terraform_generated_var_file  the CONSOLE-owned var-file holding remote_qubes
                rendered from the database. It is always passed AFTER
                terraform_var_file because terraform lets the last -var-file win
                for a given variable, and terraform replaces maps wholesale
                rather than merging them. Define remote_qubes in the base file
                too and whichever file loses the ordering silently erases the
                other's view of the fleet — the console's qubes vanish from the
                plan and the next apply destroys them.
  terraform_binary / terraform_version / terraform_url / terraform_sha256
                terraform is NOT packaged in Debian and is absent from
                debian-13-minimal, along with sqlite3, curl and git. The console
                does not embed terraform, it execs it, so this is a hard
                prerequisite and not an optional extra: without it every
                start/stop fails at exec time with "executable file not found",
                after the API call has already reported success.
                terraform_sha256 is the digest of the release zip, and config
                always wins. Empty does NOT mean unverified: install.sls carries
                known-good digests of HashiCorp's official linux_amd64 zips and
                falls back to the one for terraform_version, refusing to install
                if it has neither. The trap is pointing terraform_url at a mirror
                while leaving this empty — the built-in digest is the official
                zip's, so any mirror copy that is not byte-identical fails a
                check whose message names neither the mirror nor the fallback.
                Set it whenever the URL is not releases.hashicorp.com.
  terraform_providers  provider mirror entries (source/version/url/sha256) for
                `terraform init` without registry access. Same rule: a mirrored
                URL needs its own digest here.
  pve_endpoint  the PVE API base URL. Goes through the ingress on 443 rather
                than 10.31.0.200:8006 for two reasons: the API is only exposed
                on 443 through the ingress from this network, and the ingress
                presents a valid Let's Encrypt certificate for
                pve.infra.plz.ac, whereas hitting a node directly presents
                PVE's self-signed certificate and forces verification off on
                the connection that carries the API token. Requires cfg
                qubesair.dns to be in effect.
  pve_node      default node for placement; the cluster is heterogeneous
                (node4 runs an older PVE than the rest), so pinning matters.
  agent_listen  address the REMOTE agent binds on each provisioned qube.
  agent_package_url / agent_package_sha256 / agent_package_version
                how a booting remote qube gets the agent. The agent is
                deliberately not baked into the VM image, so this URL is the
                only path by which the binary ever reaches a remote: leave it
                empty and every new qube boots with no agent at all, which has
                already happened once here — "systemctl enable --now
                qubes-air-agent" no-opped against a unit that was never
                installed.
                SET THE URL AND THE DIGEST TOGETHER. The console refuses to
                start with a URL and no digest, on purpose: the artifact store
                accepts unauthenticated uploads and serves them over plain HTTP,
                so the digest is the ONLY integrity control in the chain. It is
                trustworthy anyway because it travels inside the cloud-init
                identity document, over a path we control. Both values are
                printed by qubes-air's scripts/publish-agent-deb.sh; paste them
                from that output rather than computing them by hand.
  apt_mirror / apt_security_mirror
                Debian mirrors for PROVISIONED REMOTE QUBES — not for this
                machine's templates, which use the cfg.mirror block above. Do
                not "fix" these to the same tuna URLs: these are LAN addresses
                on the PVE side, and the distinction is the whole point.
                Setting cloud-init user-data REPLACES the template's vendor
                data, so whatever mirror the image configured at boot stops
                applying and apt falls back to the public redirector. Measured
                on this hardware: installing two small packages took 857 of a
                15-minute provision — 99% of it — and blew the executor's
                timeout. With the LAN mirror the same step takes seconds.
                Debian serves security from a separate path, so
                apt_security_mirror is set explicitly; it falls back to
                apt_mirror when empty, which is wrong for most mirrors.
  agent_probe_interval_seconds  how often every running qube is re-probed. Zero
                or negative DISABLES the reconciler and freezes agent health at
                whatever the last probe saw — a qube that was healthy once then
                reads healthy forever, which is precisely the false-green the
                health feature exists to remove.
  agent_probe_timeout_seconds   bounds ONE probe end to end. Must stay well
                under the interval; it exists because a qube that accepts TCP
                and then goes silent would otherwise hold a probe worker
                forever, which has wedged this console before.
  agent_probe_settle_seconds    how long after a provision or resume the console
                keeps retrying before calling an agent unreachable. A fresh qube
                CANNOT answer when terraform returns — cloud-init only starts
                fetching the agent once the VM has reported its address — so
                probing once at job completion would mark every healthy qube
                unreachable. Bounded rather than infinite so a genuinely broken
                agent still produces a verdict instead of sitting in "starting".
  agent_cert_renew_interval_seconds / agent_cert_renew_threshold_percent
                fleet-wide certificate renewal sweep and the freshness
                threshold, as a percentage of total certificate lifetime.
                Disabling renewal (zero or negative) leaves cloud-init as the
                only delivery channel, and a VM reads that once at first boot —
                so rotating a certificate would mean REBUILDING the qube, and
                since every certificate in a rollout is issued within the same
                few minutes they would all expire on the same day.

qubesair secrets — NONE of these belong in this file, which is committed and is
copied wholesale to /srv/salt/slchris by scripts/setup.sh:
  QUBES_AIR_ENCRYPTION_KEY / _ENCRYPTION_KEYS  AES-256 key(s) for credentials at
    rest. A well-known insecure development key is used when unset and the
    console logs a warning; that warning is the only thing standing between a
    committed key and a fleet whose stored PVE credentials are readable by
    anyone with the repo.
  QUBES_AIR_API_TOKEN   Bearer token for /api/v1. Empty DISABLES authentication.
  the PVE API token, and the agent CA private key.
Put them in {data_dir}/secrets.env, mode 0600, owned by the service user, and
have the systemd unit read it with EnvironmentFile= so the values never appear
in a unit file, a ps listing or this repository.
-#}

